<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-654-758  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 654 758.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  July 1990 v23 n7 p63(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Error-control coding in computers. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fujiwara, Eiji; Pradhan, Dhiraj K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Coding for computers must meet restrictive speed, power, and areaconstraints, meaning an increase in speed must have acorresponding increase in the encoding and decoding speed.andP;  Codesused in actual systems include error control in high-speedmemories, requiring the code's structure to permit rapid, parallelencoding and decoding.andP;  Single-bit error-correcting and double-biterror-detecting codes are used in high-speed memories.andP;  There arealso byte error-correcting and detecting codes which detect andcorrect byte errors in addition to bit errors.andP;  Burst errors,caused by defects and dust particles, cause defects on magnetictapes and disks and optical disks.andP;  Noise in the read/write headscan cause random errors.andP;  Tape memory code and disk memory codesare used to combat these types of errors.andP;  Parity code, usingredundancy of the order duplication, achieves effective errorcontrol in processors.andP;  Unidirectional error codes are used in 4megabit VLSI ROMS and large-area liquid crystal displays fordefect tolerance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fault ToleranceError ControllersCodingReliability.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A simple odd-weight-column code and its parallel decoding circuit.andO;(chart)An H matrix for the (72,64) SEC-DED code. (chart)SbEC-DbED extension of Reed-Solomon code. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>